<p>Agent-General for New South Wales<br/>123 &amp; 125, Cannon Street,<br/>London, E.C.</p>
<p>4th May 1916.</p>
<p>My dear Ferguson,</p>
<p>I found your letter this morning on my return from the Parliamentary Commercial Committees' Congress of the Allies in Paris to which I had been invited.  I will see that it reaches your Son at once.</p>
<p>Everywhere it is the same story.  One hardly meets a family that is not in mourning, although, as a matter of fact, mourning is not worn in London now.</p>
<p>I expect your boy is in France:  about six divisions have already landed there.  They are at present well in the rear completing their training.</p>
<p>No one expects the war to end this year and it is quite possible that it will continue for another three years from now.  The Bosches at present have not a glimmer of an idea of what the Allies have done already and can do in the</p>
<p>Mr. Justice Ferguson,<br/>Supreme Court,<br/>Sydney,<br/>N.S.W.</p>
